<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-545-276  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 545 276.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>UNIX World  June 1990 v7 n6 p44(6).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Is your system safe? (security holes in UNIX operating system thatallowed Morris worm in)(includes related articles on avoidingproblems, how worm operated, microcomputer viruses)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Hayes, Frank.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The worm attack which disabled Internet in late 1988 exploitedbugs in the UNIX operating system which still linger in manyplaces.andP;  Two of the worm's attack methods involved flaws in the'sendmail' and 'fingerd' mail utilities found in the Berkeleyversion of Unix; the third was a password-guessing routine whichthe worm used to propagate itself.andP;  Quick fixes for the first twoproblems quickly became available after the worm code wasdeciphered, and UNIX vendors have released new versions of thesoftware that remove security holes.andP;  Many systems on and off theInternet have not upgraded to the new version.andP;  Another serioussecurity risk on many systems is poor passwords; users chooseobvious, easy-to-remember passwords that are also easily guessed.andO;The fundamental problem with UNIX is the fact that it was notdesigned with security in mind.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     UNIXData SecurityComputer CrimesComputer VirusesSecurity SoftwarePasswords.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>